Scotland: Norovirus Infection Affecting Several Communities in the Forth Valley
--------------------------------------------------
Winter vomiting disease is affecting several communities across the Forth
Valley. Outbreaks of [norovirus infection] have been reported in several
nurseries, schools and care homes for the elderly in recent weeks. Symptoms
include nausea, abdominal pain, vomiting, diarrhoea, headache and mild
fever, which normally develop 24-48 hours after exposure to the virus and
usually disappear within 48 hours. Anyone affected is advised to drink
plenty of fluids.
The virus is said to be most commonly spread by person-to-person contact,
although it can be spread through the air after an episode of vomiting. It
is infectious for up to 48 hours after the episode of illness. Good hygiene
reduces the risk of catching or spreading norovirus infection, and regular
hand-washing is advised.
Dr Malcolm McWhirter, director of public health for the National Health
Service (NHS) Forth Valley, said: "This is a particular problem at the
moment in the community, and I would ask anyone who has been affected by
this virus not to visit hospitals or residential care homes. The effect on
hospitals of this virus is extensive, as wards have to be closed to new
admissions and operations may have to be cancelled. "Patients who become
affected have to be kept in isolation until they recover and then for a
further 48 hours until they are symptom-free. If we cannot discharge
patients because they have been infected by this virus, then bed
availability also becomes affected. This is always a challenging time of
year for the NHS, but we are determined to keep our hospitals running as
smoothly as possible during the winter months."
--
A-Lan Banks
<A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
