Ireland: Norovirus Outbreak at Dublin Hospital
----------------------------------------------
More than 100 cases of norovirus infection [causing winter vomiting
disease] have been reported at a Dublin Hospital. Saint Vincent's Hospital
says that 76 patients and 43 staff have come down with the virus
infection. 15 wards have been closed as a result.
The hospital is appealing to people showing symptoms of the illness not to
attend its Accident and Emergency Department, to help prevent a further
spread of the illness. It is also asking the public to avoid visiting
patients if possible.
******
[4]
Date: Sat 4 Dec 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: RTE News online, Fri 3 Dec 2004 [edited]
<http://www.rte.ie/news/2004/1203/bug>

Ireland: Nurses Organization Blames Over-crowding for Norovirus Outbreak
--------------------------------------------------
The Irish Nurses Organisation (INO) has blamed overcrowding at St Vincent's
Hospital in Dublin for contributing to the spread of [norovirus infection].
There are now 160 cases of [norovirus infection] at the hospital. A
spokesman for the hospital said today that 95 patients and 65 staff had
contracted the illness. That represents an increase of 18 patient and 22
staff cases since yesterday. He added that another 45 patients are showing
symptoms of the virus. 14 wards in the hospital remain closed to new
admissions as a result of the outbreak.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[These recent outbreaks in Ireland and Scotland conform to the pattern
observed in England, where between 1992 and 2004, 79 percent of all
outbreaks reported occurred in health-care settings, either in hospitals or
residential care homes. Hotels (7 percent) and schools (5 percent) were the
next most frequent settings. - Mod.CP]
